&gt; But I am stuck here. How do I &#39;re-render&#39; the div element?

ReactJS automatically re-renders changed objects after calling the `setState()` function.

In your render function, you want to add the class based on the state.

    render() {
      if (this.state.cellValue !== &#39;empty&#39;) {
        return &lt;div onClick={() =&gt; this.fillCell(&#39;x&#39;)} className=&quot;cell filled&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;;
      } else {
        return &lt;div onClick={() =&gt; this.fillCell(&#39;x&#39;)} className=&quot;cell&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;;
      }
    }

Or the cleaner method, like @Ramjan suggested.

    render() {
      const divClass = (this.state.cellValue !== &#39;empty&#39; ? &quot;cell filled&quot; : &quot;cell&quot;);
      return &lt;div onClick={() =&gt; this.fillCell(&#39;x&#39;)} className={divClass}&gt;&lt;/div&gt;;
    }

When a state is changed, `render` is called automatically. You just have to write a condition in the `render` method to change the class name based on the current state.
For example - 

    class Cell extends React.Component {
      constructor(props) {
        super(props);
        this.state = { cellValue: &quot;empty&quot; };
      }
    
      fillCell = (player) =&gt; {
        if (player == &#39;x&#39;) {
          this.setState({ cellValue: &quot;x&quot; });
    
        } else if (player == &#39;o&#39;) {
          this.setState({ cellValue: &quot;o&quot; });
        }
      }
    
      render() {
        const { cellValue } = this.state;
        const divClass = cellValue === &#39;x&#39; ? &#39;xClassName&#39; : &#39;oClassName&#39;;
        return &lt;div onClick={() =&gt; this.fillCell(&#39;x&#39;)} className={divClass}&gt;&lt;/div&gt;;
      }
    
    }
    export default Cell;

This will re-render your `div` with new className after `fillCell` function changes the state.
Although your `fillCell` function is always receiving `x` right now.

Whenever the state is changed, render() is called automatically

so you don&#39;t have to re-render it yourself

in your case, you just have to apply the className based on some value in state

Here I have made a function that returns a string that is to be used as className 

    class Cell extends React.Component {
      constructor(props) {
        super(props);
        this.state = { cellValue: &quot;empty&quot; };
      }
    
      fillCell = player =&gt; {
        if (player == &quot;x&quot;) {
          this.setState({ cellValue: &quot;x&quot; });
        } else if (player == &quot;o&quot;) {
          this.setState({ cellValue: &quot;o&quot; });
        }
      };
    
      getClass = () =&gt; {
        const class1 = &quot;some-stlye&quot;;
        const class2 = &quot;some-other-style&quot;;
    
        if (this.state.cellValue === &quot;x&quot;) {
          return class1;
        } else if (this.state.cellValue === &quot;o&quot;) {
          return class2;
        }
      };
    
      render() {
        return &lt;div onClick={() =&gt; this.fillCell(&quot;x&quot;)} className={getClass()}&gt;&lt;/div&gt;;
      }
    }
    export default Cell;

Note that i have called the getClass, not just gave its reference, so it runs whenever the render is called and return a string which will be used as className

